# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: address-space-layout-randomization
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/address-space-layout-randomization] The Linux PaX project first coined the term "ASLR", and published the first design and implementation of ASLR in July 2001 as a patch for the Linux kernel.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/address-space-layout-randomization] It is seen as a complete implementation, providing a patch for kernel stack randomization since October 2002.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/address-space-layout-randomization] The first mainstream operating system to support ASLR by default was OpenBSD version 3.4 in 2003, followed by Linux in 2005.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/address-space-layout-randomization] Address space randomization hinders some types of security attacks by making it more difficult for an attacker to predict target addresses.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/address-space-layout-randomization] For example, attackers trying to execute return-to-libc attacks must locate the code to be executed, while other attackers trying to execute shellcode injected on the stack have to find the stack first.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/address-space-layout-randomization] In both cases, the system makes related memory-addresses unpredictable from the attackers' point of view.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/address-space-layout-randomization] These values have to be guessed, and a mistaken guess is not usually recoverable due to the application crashing.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/address-space-layout-randomization] Address space layout randomization is based upon the low chance of an attacker guessing the locations of randomly placed areas.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/address-space-layout-randomization] Security is increased by increasing the search space.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/address-space-layout-randomization] Thus, address space randomization is more effective when more entropy is present in the random offsets.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/address-space-layout-randomization] Entropy is increased by either raising the amount of virtual memory area space over which the randomization occurs or reducing the period over which the randomization occurs.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/address-space-layout-randomization] The period is typically implemented as small as possible, so most systems must increase VMA space randomization.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/address-space-layout-randomization] To defeat the randomization, attackers must successfully guess the positions of all areas they wish to attack.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/address-space-layout-randomization] For data areas such as stack and heap, where custom code or useful data can be loaded, more than one state can be attacked by using NOP slides for code or repeated copies of data.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/address-space-layout-randomization] This allows an attack to succeed if the area is randomized to one of a handful of values.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/address-space-layout-randomization] In contrast, code areas such as library base and main executable need to be discovered exactly.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/address-space-layout-randomization] Often these areas are mixed, for example stack frames are injected onto the stack and a library is returned into.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/address-space-layout-randomization] To calculate the probability of an attacker succeeding, a number of attempts α carried out without being interrupted by a signature-based IPS, law enforcement, or other factor must be assumed; in the case of brute forcing, the daemon cannot be restarted.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/address-space-layout-randomization] The number of relevant bits and how many are being attacked in each attempt must also be calculated, leaving however many bits the attacker has to defeat.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/address-space-layout-randomization] The following formulas represent the probability of success for a given set of α attempts on N bits of entropy.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/address-space-layout-randomization] In many systems, $2^{N}$ can be in the thousands or millions.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/address-space-layout-randomization] On 32-bit systems, a typical amount of entropy *N* is 8 bits.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/address-space-layout-randomization] For 2004 computer speeds, Shacham and co-workers state "...
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/address-space-layout-randomization] 16 bits of address randomization can be defeated by a brute force attack within minutes." (The authors' statement depends on the ability to attack the same application multiple times without any delay.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/address-space-layout-randomization] Proper implementations of ASLR, like that included in grsecurity, provide several methods to make such brute force attacks infeasible.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/address-space-layout-randomization] One method involves preventing an executable from executing for a configurable amount of time if it has crashed a certain number of times.) On modern 64-bit systems, these numbers typically reach the millions at least.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/address-space-layout-randomization] Android, and possibly other systems, implement *Library Load Order Randomization*, a form of ASLR which randomizes the order in which libraries are loaded.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/address-space-layout-randomization] An approximation of the number of bits of entropy supplied per needed library appears below; this does not yet account for varied library sizes, so the actual entropy gained is really somewhat higher.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/address-space-layout-randomization] Attackers usually need only one library; the math is more complex with multiple libraries, and shown below as well.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/address-space-layout-randomization] The case of an attacker using only one library is a simplification of the more complex formula for $l=1$ .
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/address-space-layout-randomization] These values tend to be low even for large values of l, most importantly since attackers typically can use only the C standard library and thus one can often assume that $\beta \,=1$ .
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/address-space-layout-randomization] However, even for a small number of libraries there are a few bits of entropy gained here; it is thus potentially interesting to combine library load order randomization with VMA address randomization to gain a few extra bits of entropy.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/address-space-layout-randomization] These extra bits of entropy will not apply to other mmap() segments, only libraries.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/address-space-layout-randomization] Attackers may make use of several methods to reduce the entropy present in a randomized address space, ranging from simple information leaks to attacking multiple bits of entropy per attack (such as by heap spraying).
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/address-space-layout-randomization] There is little that can be done about this.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/address-space-layout-randomization] It is possible to leak information about memory layout using format string vulnerabilities.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/address-space-layout-randomization] Format string functions such as printf use a variable argument list to do their job; format specifiers describe what the argument list looks like.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/address-space-layout-randomization] Because of the way arguments are typically passed, each format specifier moves closer to the top of the stack frame.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/address-space-layout-randomization] Eventually, the return pointer and stack frame pointer can be extracted, revealing the address of a vulnerable library and the address of a known stack frame; this can eliminate library and stack randomization as an obstacle to an attacker.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/address-space-layout-randomization] One can also decrease entropy in the stack or heap.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/address-space-layout-randomization] The stack typically must be aligned to 16 bytes, and so this is the smallest possible randomization interval; while the heap must be page-aligned, typically 4096 bytes.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/address-space-layout-randomization] When attempting an attack, it is possible to align duplicate attacks with these intervals; a NOP slide may be used with shellcode injection, and the string '`/bin/sh`' can be replaced with '`////////bin/sh`' for an arbitrary number of slashes when attempting to return to *system*.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/address-space-layout-randomization] The number of bits removed is exactly $\log _{2}\!\left(n\right)$ for n intervals attacked.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/address-space-layout-randomization] Such decreases are limited due to the amount of data in the stack or heap.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/address-space-layout-randomization] The stack, for example, is typically limited to 8 MB and grows to much less; this allows for at most 19 bits, although a more conservative estimate would be around 8–10 bits corresponding to 4–16 KB of stack stuffing.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/address-space-layout-randomization] The heap on the other hand is limited by the behavior of the memory allocator; in the case of glibc, allocations above 128 KB are created using mmap, limiting attackers to 5 bits of reduction.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/address-space-layout-randomization] This is also a limiting factor when brute forcing; although the number of attacks to perform can be reduced, the size of the attacks is increased enough that the behavior could in some circumstances become apparent to intrusion detection systems.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/address-space-layout-randomization] ASLR-protected addresses can be leaked by various side channels, removing mitigation utility.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/address-space-layout-randomization] Recent attacks have used information leaked by the CPU branch target predictor buffer (BTB) or memory management unit (MMU) walking page tables.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/address-space-layout-randomization] It is not clear if this class of ASLR attack can be mitigated.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/address-space-layout-randomization] If they cannot, the benefit of ASLR is reduced or eliminated.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/address-space-layout-randomization] In August 2024 a paper was published with an empirical analysis of major desktop platforms, including Linux, macOS, and Windows, by examining the variability in the placement of memory objects across various processes, threads, and system restarts.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/address-space-layout-randomization] The results show that while some systems as of 2024, like Linux distributions, provide robust randomization, others, like Windows and macOS, often fail to adequately randomize key areas like executable code and libraries.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/address-space-layout-randomization] Moreover, they found a significant reduction in the entropy of libraries after the Linux 5.18 version and identify correlation paths that an attacker could leverage to reduce exploitation complexity significantly.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/address-space-layout-randomization] Several mainstream, general-purpose operating systems implement ASLR.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/address-space-layout-randomization] Android 4.0 Ice Cream Sandwich provides address space layout randomization (ASLR) to help protect system and third-party applications from exploits due to memory-management issues.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/address-space-layout-randomization] Position-independent executable support was added in Android 4.1.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/address-space-layout-randomization] Android 5.0 dropped non-PIE support and requires all dynamically linked binaries to be position independent.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/address-space-layout-randomization] Library load ordering randomization was accepted into the Android open-source project on 26 October 2015, and was included in the Android 7.0 release.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/address-space-layout-randomization] DragonFly BSD has an implementation of ASLR based upon OpenBSD's model, added in 2010.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/address-space-layout-randomization] It is off by default, and can be enabled by setting the sysctl vm.randomize_mmap to 1.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/address-space-layout-randomization] Support for ASLR appeared in FreeBSD 13.0.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/address-space-layout-randomization] Apple introduced ASLR in iOS 4.3 (released March 2011).
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/address-space-layout-randomization] The randomized kernel base is `0x01000000 + ((1+0xRR) * 0x00200000)`, where `0xRR` is a random byte from SHA1 (random data) generated by iBoot (the 2nd-stage iOS Boot Loader).
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/address-space-layout-randomization] The Linux kernel enabled a weak form of ASLR by default since the kernel version 2.6.12, released in June 2005.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/address-space-layout-randomization] The PaX and Exec Shield patchsets to the Linux kernel provide more complete implementations.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/address-space-layout-randomization] The Exec Shield patch for Linux supplies 19 bits of stack entropy on a period of 16 bytes, and 8 bits of mmap base randomization on a period of 1 page of 4096 bytes.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/address-space-layout-randomization] This places the stack base in an area 8 MB wide containing 524,288 possible positions, and the mmap base in an area 1 MB wide containing 256 possible positions.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/address-space-layout-randomization] ASLR can be disabled for a specific process by changing its execution domain, using `personality(2)`.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/address-space-layout-randomization] A number of sysctl options control the behavior of mainline ASLR.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/address-space-layout-randomization] For example, `kernel.randomize_va_space` controls *what* to randomize; the strongest option is 2.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/address-space-layout-randomization] `vm.mmap_rnd_bits` controls how many bits to randomize for mmap.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/address-space-layout-randomization] Position-independent executable (PIE) implements a random base address for the main executable binary and has been in place since April 18, 2004.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/address-space-layout-randomization] It provides the same address randomness to the main executable as being used for the shared libraries.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/address-space-layout-randomization] The PIE feature cannot be used together with the prelink feature for the same executable.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/address-space-layout-randomization] The prelink tool implements randomization at prelink time rather than runtime, because by design prelink aims to handle relocating libraries before the dynamic linker has to, which allows the relocation to occur once for many runs of the program.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/address-space-layout-randomization] As a result, real address space randomization would defeat the purpose of prelinking.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/address-space-layout-randomization] In 2014, Marco-Gisbert and Ripoll disclosed *offset2lib* technique that weakens Linux ASLR for PIE executables.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/address-space-layout-randomization] Linux kernels load PIE executables right after their libraries; as a result, there is a fixed offset between the executable and the library functions.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/address-space-layout-randomization] If an attacker finds a way to find the address of a function in the executable, the library addresses are also known.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/address-space-layout-randomization] They demonstrated an attack that finds the address in fewer than 400 tries.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/address-space-layout-randomization] They proposed a new `randomize_va_space=3` option to randomize the placement of the executable relative to the library, but it is yet to be incorporated into the upstream as of 2024.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/address-space-layout-randomization] The Linux kernel 5.18 released May 2022 reduced the effectiveness of both 32-bit and 64-bit implementations.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/address-space-layout-randomization] Linux filesystems call `thp_get_unmapped_area` to respond to a file-backed mmap.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/address-space-layout-randomization] With a change in 5.18, files greater than 2 MiB are made to return 2 MiB-aligned addresses, so they can be potentially backed by huge pages.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/address-space-layout-randomization] For 32-bit Linux, many distributions show no randomization *at all* in the placement of the libc.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/address-space-layout-randomization] For 64-bit Linux, the 28 bits of entropy is reduced to 19 bits.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/address-space-layout-randomization] In response, Ubuntu has increased its `mmap_rnd_bits` setting.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/address-space-layout-randomization] Martin Doucha added a Linux Test Project testcase to detect this issue.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/address-space-layout-randomization] Kernel address space layout randomization (KASLR) enables address space randomization for the Linux kernel image by randomizing where the kernel code is placed at boot time.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/address-space-layout-randomization] KASLR was merged into the Linux kernel mainline in kernel version 3.14, released on 30 March 2014.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/address-space-layout-randomization] When compiled in, it can be disabled at boot time by specifying nokaslr as one of the kernel's boot parameters.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/address-space-layout-randomization] There are several side-channel attacks in x86 processors that could leak kernel addresses.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/address-space-layout-randomization] In late 2017, kernel page-table isolation (KPTI aka KAISER) was developed to defeat these attacks.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/address-space-layout-randomization] However, this method cannot protect against side-channel attacks utilizing collisions in branch predictor structures.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/address-space-layout-randomization] As of 2021, finer grained kernel address space layout randomization (or function granular KASLR, FGKASLR) is a planned extension of KASLR to randomize down to the function level by placing functions in separate sections and reordering them at boot time.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/address-space-layout-randomization] Microsoft's Windows Vista (released *to manufacturing* November 2006, generally available January 2007) and later have ASLR enabled only for executables and dynamic link libraries that are specifically linked to be ASLR-enabled.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/address-space-layout-randomization] For compatibility, it is not enabled by default for other applications.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/address-space-layout-randomization] Typically, only older software is incompatible and ASLR can be fully enabled by editing a registry entry `HKLM\SYSTEM\CurrentControlSet\Control\Session Manager\Memory Management\MoveImages`, or by installing Microsoft's Enhanced Mitigation Experience Toolkit.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/address-space-layout-randomization] The locations of the heap, stack, Process Environment Block, and Thread Environment Block are also randomized.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/address-space-layout-randomization] A security whitepaper from Symantec noted that ASLR in 32-bit Windows Vista may not be as robust as expected, and Microsoft has acknowledged a weakness in its implementation.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/address-space-layout-randomization] Host-based intrusion prevention systems such as *WehnTrust* and *Ozone* also offer ASLR for Windows XP and Windows Server 2003 operating systems.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/address-space-layout-randomization] Complete details of Ozone's implementation are not available.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/address-space-layout-randomization] It was noted in February 2012 that ASLR on 32-bit Windows systems prior to Windows 8 can have its effectiveness reduced in low memory situations.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/address-space-layout-randomization] A similar effect also had been achieved on Linux in the same research.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/address-space-layout-randomization] The test code caused the Mac OS X 10.7.3 system to kernel panic, so it was left unclear about its ASLR behavior in this scenario.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/address-space-layout-randomization] Support for ASLR in userland appeared in NetBSD 5.0 (released April 2009), and was enabled by default in NetBSD-current in April 2016.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/address-space-layout-randomization] Kernel ASLR support on amd64 was added in NetBSD-current in October 2017, making NetBSD the first BSD system to support KASLR.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/address-space-layout-randomization] In 2003, OpenBSD became the first mainstream operating system to support a strong form of ASLR and to activate it by default.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/address-space-layout-randomization] OpenBSD completed its ASLR support in 2008 when it added support for PIE binaries.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/address-space-layout-randomization] OpenBSD 4.4's malloc(3) was designed to improve security by taking advantage of ASLR and gap page features implemented as part of OpenBSD's `mmap` system call, and to detect use-after-free bugs.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/address-space-layout-randomization] Released in 2013, OpenBSD 5.3 was the first mainstream operating system to enable position-independent executables by default on multiple hardware platforms, and OpenBSD 5.7 activated position-independent static binaries (Static-PIE) by default.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/address-space-layout-randomization] In Mac OS X Leopard 10.5 (released October 2007), Apple introduced randomization for system libraries.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/address-space-layout-randomization] In Mac OS X Lion 10.7 (released July 2011), Apple expanded their implementation to cover all applications, stating "address space layout randomization (ASLR) has been improved for all applications.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/address-space-layout-randomization] As of OS X Mountain Lion 10.8 (released July 2012) and later, the entire system including the kernel as well as kexts and zones are randomly relocated during system boot.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/address-space-layout-randomization] ASLR has been introduced in Solaris beginning with Solaris 11.1 (released October 2012).
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/address-space-layout-randomization] ASLR in Solaris 11.1 can be set system-wide, per zone, or on a per-binary basis.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/address-space-layout-randomization] A side-channel attack utilizing branch target buffer was demonstrated to bypass ASLR protection.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/address-space-layout-randomization] In 2017, an attack named "ASLR⊕Cache" was demonstrated which could defeat ASLR in a web browser using JavaScript.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/buffer-overflow] In programming and information security, a **buffer overflow** or **buffer overrun** is an anomaly whereby a program writes data to a buffer beyond the buffer's allocated memory, overwriting adjacent memory locations.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/buffer-overflow] Buffers are areas of memory set aside to hold data, often while moving it from one section of a program to another, or between programs.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/buffer-overflow] Buffer overflows can often be triggered by malformed inputs; if one assumes all inputs will be smaller than a certain size and the buffer is created to be that size, then an anomalous transaction that produces more data could cause it to write past the end of the buffer.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/buffer-overflow] If this overwrites adjacent data or executable code, this may result in erratic program behavior, including memory access errors, incorrect results, and crashes.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/buffer-overflow] Exploiting the behavior of a buffer overflow is a well-known security exploit.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/buffer-overflow] Files specifically created to exploit buffer overflow vulnerabilities are often called 'crafted' files.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/buffer-overflow] On many systems, the memory layout of a program, or the system as a whole, is well defined.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/buffer-overflow] Buffers are widespread in operating system (OS) code, so it is possible to make attacks that perform privilege escalation and gain unlimited access to the computer's resources.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/buffer-overflow] The famed Morris worm in 1988 used this as one of its attack techniques.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/buffer-overflow] Bounds checking can prevent buffer overflows, but requires additional code and processing time.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/buffer-overflow] Modern operating systems use a variety of techniques to combat malicious buffer overflows, notably by randomizing the layout of memory, or deliberately leaving space between buffers and looking for actions that write into those areas ("canaries").
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/buffer-overflow] A buffer overflow occurs when data written to a buffer also corrupts data values in memory addresses adjacent to the destination buffer due to insufficient bounds checking.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/buffer-overflow] This can occur when copying data from one buffer to another without first checking that the data fits within the destination buffer.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/buffer-overflow] In the following example expressed in C, a program has two variables which are adjacent in memory: an 8-byte-long string buffer, `a`, and a two-byte big-endian integer, `b`.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/buffer-overflow] Initially, `a` contains nothing but zero bytes, and `b` contains the number 1979.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/buffer-overflow] Now, the program attempts to store the null-terminated string `"excessive"` with ASCII encoding in the A buffer.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/buffer-overflow] `"excessive"` is 9 characters long and encodes to 10 bytes including the null terminator, but `a` can take only 8 bytes.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/buffer-overflow] `b`'s value has now been inadvertently replaced by a number formed from part of the character string.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/buffer-overflow] In this example "e" followed by a zero byte would become 25856.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/buffer-overflow] Writing data past the end of allocated memory can sometimes be detected by the operating system to generate a segmentation fault error that terminates the process.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/buffer-overflow] When available, the strlcpy library function is preferred over strncpy which does not null-terminate the destination buffer if the source string's length is greater than or equal to the size of the buffer (the third argument passed to the function).
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/buffer-overflow] Therefore a may not be null-terminated and cannot be treated as a valid C-style string.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/buffer-overflow] The techniques to exploit a buffer overflow vulnerability vary by architecture, operating system, and memory region.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/buffer-overflow] For example, exploitation on the heap (used for dynamically allocated memory), differs markedly from exploitation on the call stack.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/buffer-overflow] In general, heap exploitation depends on the heap manager used on the target system, while stack exploitation depends on the calling convention used by the architecture and compiler.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/buffer-overflow] The attacker designs data to cause one of these exploits, then places this data in a buffer supplied to users by the vulnerable code.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/buffer-overflow] If the address of the user-supplied data used to affect the stack buffer overflow is unpredictable, exploiting a stack buffer overflow to cause remote code execution becomes much more difficult.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/buffer-overflow] One technique that can be used to exploit such a buffer overflow is called "trampolining".
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/buffer-overflow] Here, an attacker will find a pointer to the vulnerable stack buffer and compute the location of their shellcode relative to that pointer.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/buffer-overflow] The attacker will then use the overwrite to jump to an instruction already in memory which will make a second jump, this time relative to the pointer.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/buffer-overflow] That second jump will branch execution into the shellcode.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/buffer-overflow] Suitable instructions are often present in large code.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/buffer-overflow] The Metasploit Project, for example, maintains a database of suitable opcodes, though it lists only those found in the Windows operating system.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/buffer-overflow] A buffer overflow occurring in the heap data area is referred to as a heap overflow and is exploitable in a manner different from that of stack-based overflows.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/buffer-overflow] Memory on the heap is dynamically allocated by the application at run-time and typically contains program data.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/buffer-overflow] Exploitation is performed by corrupting this data in specific ways to cause the application to overwrite internal structures such as linked list pointers.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/buffer-overflow] The canonical heap overflow technique overwrites dynamic memory allocation linkage (such as malloc meta data) and uses the resulting pointer exchange to overwrite a program function pointer.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/buffer-overflow] Microsoft's GDI+ vulnerability in handling JPEGs is an example of the danger a heap overflow can present.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/buffer-overflow] Manipulation of the buffer, which occurs before it is read or executed, may lead to the failure of an exploitation attempt.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/buffer-overflow] These manipulations can mitigate the threat of exploitation, but may not make it impossible.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/buffer-overflow] Manipulations could include conversion to upper or lower case, removal of metacharacters and filtering out of non-alphanumeric strings.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/buffer-overflow] However, techniques exist to bypass these filters and manipulations, such as alphanumeric shellcode, polymorphic code, self-modifying code, and return-to-libc attacks.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/buffer-overflow] The same methods can be used to avoid detection by intrusion detection systems.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/buffer-overflow] In some cases, including where code is converted into Unicode, the threat of the vulnerability has been misrepresented by the disclosers as only Denial of Service when in fact the remote execution of arbitrary code is possible.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/buffer-overflow] In real-world exploits there are a variety of challenges which need to be overcome for exploits to operate reliably.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/buffer-overflow] These factors include null bytes in addresses, variability in the location of shellcode, differences between environments, and various counter-measures in operation.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/buffer-overflow] A NOP-sled is the oldest and most widely known technique for exploiting stack buffer overflows.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/buffer-overflow] It solves the problem of finding the exact address of the buffer by effectively increasing the size of the target area.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/buffer-overflow] To do this, much larger sections of the stack are corrupted with the no-op machine instruction.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/buffer-overflow] At the end of the attacker-supplied data, after the no-op instructions, the attacker places an instruction to perform a relative jump to the top of the buffer where the shellcode is located.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/buffer-overflow] This collection of no-ops is referred to as the "NOP-sled" because if the return address is overwritten with any address within the no-op region of the buffer, the execution will "slide" down the no-ops until it is redirected to the actual malicious code by the jump at the end.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/buffer-overflow] This technique requires the attacker to guess where on the stack the NOP-sled is instead of the comparatively small shellcode.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/buffer-overflow] Because of the popularity of this technique, many vendors of intrusion prevention systems will search for this pattern of no-op machine instructions in an attempt to detect shellcode in use.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/buffer-overflow] A NOP-sled does not necessarily contain only traditional no-op machine instructions.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/buffer-overflow] Any instruction that does not corrupt the machine state to a point where the shellcode will not run can be used in place of the hardware assisted no-op.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/buffer-overflow] As a result, it has become common practice for exploit writers to compose the no-op sled with randomly chosen instructions which will have no real effect on the shellcode execution.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/buffer-overflow] While this method greatly improves the chances that an attack will be successful, it is not without problems.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/buffer-overflow] Exploits using this technique still must rely on some amount of luck that they will guess offsets on the stack that are within the NOP-sled region.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/buffer-overflow] An incorrect guess will usually result in the target program crashing and could alert the system administrator to the attacker's activities.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/buffer-overflow] Another problem is that the NOP-sled requires a much larger amount of memory in which to hold a NOP-sled large enough to be of any use.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/buffer-overflow] This can be a problem when the allocated size of the affected buffer is too small and the current depth of the stack is shallow (i.e., there is not much space from the end of the current stack frame to the start of the stack).
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/buffer-overflow] Despite its problems, the NOP-sled is often the only method that will work for a given platform, environment, or situation, and as such it is still an important technique.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/buffer-overflow] The "jump to register" technique allows for reliable exploitation of stack buffer overflows without the need for extra room for a NOP-sled and without having to guess stack offsets.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/buffer-overflow] The strategy is to overwrite the return pointer with something that will cause the program to jump to a known pointer stored within a register which points to the controlled buffer and thus the shellcode.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/buffer-overflow] For example, if register A contains a pointer to the start of a buffer then any jump or call taking that register as an operand can be used to gain control of the flow of execution.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/buffer-overflow] In practice a program may not intentionally contain instructions to jump to a particular register.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/buffer-overflow] The traditional solution is to find an unintentional instance of a suitable opcode at a fixed location somewhere within the program memory.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/buffer-overflow] Figure E on the left contains an example of such an unintentional instance of the i386 `jmp esp` instruction.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/buffer-overflow] The opcode for this instruction is `FF E4`.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/buffer-overflow] This two-byte sequence can be found at a one-byte offset from the start of the instruction `call DbgPrint` at address `0x7C941EED`.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/buffer-overflow] If an attacker overwrites the program return address with this address the program will first jump to `0x7C941EED`, interpret the opcode `FF E4` as the `jmp esp` instruction, and will then jump to the top of the stack and execute the attacker's code.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/buffer-overflow] When this technique is possible the severity of the vulnerability increases considerably.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/buffer-overflow] This is because exploitation will work reliably enough to automate an attack with a virtual guarantee of success when it is run.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/buffer-overflow] For this reason, this is the technique most commonly used in Internet worms that exploit stack buffer overflow vulnerabilities.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/buffer-overflow] This method also allows shellcode to be placed after the overwritten return address on the Windows platform.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/buffer-overflow] Since executables are mostly based at address `0x00400000` and x86 is a little endian architecture, the last byte of the return address must be a null, which terminates the buffer copy and nothing is written beyond that.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/buffer-overflow] This limits the size of the shellcode to the size of the buffer, which may be overly restrictive.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/buffer-overflow] DLLs are located in high memory (above `0x01000000`) and so have addresses containing no null bytes, so this method can remove null bytes (or other disallowed characters) from the overwritten return address.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/buffer-overflow] Used in this way, the method is often referred to as **DLL trampolining**.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/buffer-overflow] Various techniques have been used to detect or prevent buffer overflows, with various tradeoffs.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/buffer-overflow] The following sections describe the choices and implementations available.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/buffer-overflow] Assembly, C, and C++ are popular programming languages that are vulnerable to buffer overflow in part because they allow direct access to memory and are not strongly typed.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/buffer-overflow] C provides no built-in protection against accessing or overwriting data in any part of memory.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/buffer-overflow] More specifically, it does not check that data written to a buffer is within the boundaries of that buffer.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/buffer-overflow] The standard C++ libraries provide many ways of safely buffering data, and C++'s Standard Template Library (STL) provides containers that can optionally perform bounds checking if the programmer explicitly calls for checks while accessing data.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/buffer-overflow] For example, a `vector`'s member function `at()` performs a bounds check and throws an `out_of_range` exception if the bounds check fails.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/buffer-overflow] However, C++ behaves just like C if the bounds check is not explicitly called.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/buffer-overflow] Techniques to avoid buffer overflows also exist for C.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/buffer-overflow] Languages that are strongly typed and do not allow direct memory access, such as COBOL, Java, Eiffel, Python, and others, prevent buffer overflow in most cases.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/buffer-overflow] Examples of such languages include Ada, Eiffel, Lisp, Modula-2, Smalltalk, OCaml and some systems programming languages such as Cyclone, Rust and D.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/buffer-overflow] The Java and .NET Framework bytecode environments also require bounds checking on all arrays.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/buffer-overflow] Nearly every interpreted language will protect against buffer overflow, signaling a well-defined error condition.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/buffer-overflow] Languages that provide enough type information to do bounds checking often provide an option to enable or disable it.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/buffer-overflow] Static code analysis can remove many dynamic bound and type checks, but poor implementations and awkward cases can significantly decrease performance.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/buffer-overflow] Software engineers should carefully consider the tradeoffs of safety versus performance costs when deciding which language and compiler setting to use.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/buffer-overflow] The problem of buffer overflows is common in the C and C++ languages because they expose low level representational details of buffers as containers for data types.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/buffer-overflow] Buffer overflows can be avoided by maintaining a high degree of correctness in code that performs buffer management.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/buffer-overflow] It has also long been recommended to avoid standard library functions that are not bounds checked, such as `gets`, `scanf` and `strcpy`.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/buffer-overflow] The Morris worm exploited a `gets` call in fingerd.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/buffer-overflow] Well-written and tested abstract data type libraries that centralize and automatically perform buffer management, including bounds checking, can reduce the occurrence and impact of buffer overflows.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/buffer-overflow] The primary data types in languages in which buffer overflows are common are strings and arrays.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/buffer-overflow] Thus, libraries preventing buffer overflows in these data types can provide the vast majority of the necessary coverage.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/buffer-overflow] However, failure to use these safe libraries correctly can result in buffer overflows and other vulnerabilities, and naturally any bug in the library is also a potential vulnerability.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/buffer-overflow] "Safe" library implementations include "The Better String Library", Vstr and Erwin.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/buffer-overflow] The OpenBSD operating system's C library provides the strlcpy and strlcat functions, but these are more limited than full safe library implementations.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/buffer-overflow] In September 2007, Technical Report 24731, prepared by the C standards committee, was published.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/buffer-overflow] It specifies a set of functions that are based on the standard C library's string and IO functions, with additional buffer-size parameters.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/buffer-overflow] However, the efficacy of these functions for reducing buffer overflows is disputable.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/buffer-overflow] They require programmer intervention on a per function call basis that is equivalent to intervention that could make the analogous older standard library functions buffer overflow safe.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/buffer-overflow] Buffer overflow protection is used to detect the most common buffer overflows by checking that the stack has not been altered when a function returns.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/buffer-overflow] If it has been altered, the program exits with a segmentation fault.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/buffer-overflow] Three such systems are Libsafe, and the *StackGuard* and *ProPolice* gcc patches.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/buffer-overflow] Microsoft's implementation of Data Execution Prevention (DEP) mode explicitly protects the pointer to the Structured Exception Handler (SEH) from being overwritten.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/buffer-overflow] Stronger stack protection is possible by splitting the stack in two: one for data and one for function returns.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/buffer-overflow] This split is present in the Forth language, though it was not a security-based design decision.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/buffer-overflow] Regardless, this is not a complete solution to buffer overflows, as sensitive data other than the return address may still be overwritten.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/buffer-overflow] This type of protection is also not entirely accurate because it does not detect all attacks.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/buffer-overflow] Systems like StackGuard are more centered around the behavior of the attacks, which makes them efficient and faster in comparison to range-check systems.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/buffer-overflow] Buffer overflows work by manipulating pointers, including stored addresses.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/buffer-overflow] PointGuard was proposed as a compiler-extension to prevent attackers from reliably manipulating pointers and addresses.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/buffer-overflow] The approach works by having the compiler add code to automatically XOR-encode pointers before and after they are used.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/buffer-overflow] Theoretically, because the attacker does not know what value will be used to encode and decode the pointer, one cannot predict what the pointer will point to if it is overwritten with a new value.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/buffer-overflow] PointGuard was never released, but Microsoft implemented a similar approach beginning in Windows XP SP2 and Windows Server 2003 SP1.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/buffer-overflow] Rather than implement pointer protection as an automatic feature, Microsoft added an API routine that can be called.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/buffer-overflow] This allows for better performance (because it is not used all of the time), but places the burden on the programmer to know when its use is necessary.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/buffer-overflow] Because XOR is linear, an attacker may be able to manipulate an encoded pointer by overwriting only the lower bytes of an address.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/buffer-overflow] This can allow an attack to succeed if the attacker can attempt the exploit multiple times or complete an attack by causing a pointer to point to one of several locations (such as any location within a NOP sled).
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/buffer-overflow] Microsoft added a random rotation to their encoding scheme to address this weakness to partial overwrites.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/buffer-overflow] Executable-space protection is an approach to buffer overflow protection that prevents execution of code on the stack or the heap.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/buffer-overflow] An attacker may use buffer overflows to insert arbitrary code into the memory of a program, but with executable-space protection, any attempt to execute that code will cause an exception.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/buffer-overflow] Some CPUs support a feature called NX ("No eXecute") or XD ("eXecute Disabled") bit, which in conjunction with software, can be used to mark pages of data (such as those containing the stack and the heap) as readable and writable but not executable.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/buffer-overflow] OpenBSD, macOS) ship with executable-space protection (e.g.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/buffer-overflow] Newer variants of Microsoft Windows also support executable-space protection, called Data Execution Prevention.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/buffer-overflow] Executable-space protection does not generally protect against return-to-libc attacks, or any other attack that does not rely on the execution of the attackers code.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/buffer-overflow] However, on 64-bit systems using ASLR, as described below, executable-space protection makes it far more difficult to execute such attacks.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/buffer-overflow] CHERI (Capability Hardware Enhanced RISC Instructions) is a computer processor technology designed to improve security.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/buffer-overflow] It operates at a hardware level by providing a hardware-enforced type (a CHERI capability) that authorises access to memory.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/buffer-overflow] Traditional pointers are replaced by addresses accompanied by metadata that limit what can be accessed through any given pointer.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/buffer-overflow] Address space layout randomization (ASLR) is a computer security feature that involves arranging the positions of key data areas, usually including the base of the executable and position of libraries, heap, and stack, randomly in a process' address space.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/buffer-overflow] Randomization of the virtual memory addresses at which functions and variables can be found can make exploitation of a buffer overflow more difficult, but not impossible.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/buffer-overflow] It also forces the attacker to tailor the exploitation attempt to the individual system, which foils the attempts of internet worms.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/buffer-overflow] A similar but less effective method is to rebase processes and libraries in the virtual address space.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/buffer-overflow] The use of deep packet inspection (DPI) can detect, at the network perimeter, very basic remote attempts to exploit buffer overflows by use of attack signatures and heuristics.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/buffer-overflow] This technique can block packets that have the signature of a known attack.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/buffer-overflow] It was formerly used in situations in which a long series of No-Operation instructions (known as a NOP-sled) was detected and the location of the exploit's payload was slightly variable.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/buffer-overflow] Packet scanning is not an effective method since it can only prevent known attacks and there are many ways that a NOP-sled can be encoded.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/buffer-overflow] Shellcode used by attackers can be made alphanumeric, metamorphic, or self-modifying to evade detection by heuristic packet scanners and intrusion detection systems.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/buffer-overflow] Checking for buffer overflows and patching the bugs that cause them helps prevent buffer overflows.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/buffer-overflow] One common automated technique for discovering them is fuzzing.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/buffer-overflow] Edge case testing can also uncover buffer overflows, as can static analysis.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/buffer-overflow] Once a potential buffer overflow is detected it should be patched.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/buffer-overflow] This makes the testing approach useful for software that is in development, but less useful for legacy software that is no longer maintained or supported.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/buffer-overflow] This can be used to inject code into the monitor that will permit the user to seize control of the machine." Today, the monitor would be referred to as the kernel.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/buffer-overflow] The earliest documented hostile exploitation of a buffer overflow was in 1988.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/buffer-overflow] It was one of several exploits used by the Morris worm to propagate itself over the Internet.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/buffer-overflow] The program exploited was a service on Unix called finger.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/buffer-overflow] Later, in 1995, Thomas Lopatic independently rediscovered the buffer overflow and published his findings on the Bugtraq security mailing list.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/buffer-overflow] A year later, in 1996, Elias Levy (also known as Aleph One) published in *Phrack* magazine the paper "Smashing the Stack for Fun and Profit", a step-by-step introduction to exploiting stack-based buffer overflow vulnerabilities.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/buffer-overflow] Since then, at least two major internet worms have exploited buffer overflows to compromise a large number of systems.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/buffer-overflow] In 2001, the Code Red worm exploited a buffer overflow in Microsoft's Internet Information Services (IIS) 5.0 and in 2003 the SQL Slammer worm compromised machines running Microsoft SQL Server 2000.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/buffer-overflow] In 2003, buffer overflows present in licensed Xbox games have been exploited to allow unlicensed software, including homebrew games, to run on the console without the need for hardware modifications, known as modchips.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/buffer-overflow] The PS2 Independence Exploit also used a buffer overflow to achieve the same for the PlayStation 2.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/buffer-overflow] The Twilight hack accomplished the same with the Wii, using a buffer overflow in *The Legend of Zelda: Twilight Princess*.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/data-segment] In computing, a **data segment** (often denoted **.data**) is a portion of an object file or the corresponding address space of a program that contains initialized static variables, that is, global variables and static local variables.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/data-segment] The size of this segment is determined by the size of the values in the program's source code and does not change at run time.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/data-segment] The data segment is read/write, since the values of variables can be altered at run time.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/data-segment] This is in contrast to the *read-only data segment* (*rodata segment* or *.rodata*), which contains static constants rather than variables; it also contrasts to the code segment, also known as the text segment, which is read-only on many architectures.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/data-segment] Uninitialized data, both variables and constants, is instead in the .bss segment.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/data-segment] Historically, to be able to support memory address spaces larger than the native size of the internal address register would allow, early CPUs implemented a system of segmentation whereby they would store a small set of indexes to use as offsets to certain areas.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/data-segment] The Intel 8086 family of CPUs provided four segments: the code segment, the data segment, the stack segment and the extra segment.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/data-segment] Each segment was placed at a specific location in memory by the software being executed, and all instructions that operated on the data within those segments were performed relative to the start of that segment.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/data-segment] This allowed a 16-bit address register, which would normally be able to access 64 KB of memory space, to access 1 MB of memory space.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/data-segment] This segmenting of the memory space into discrete blocks with specific tasks carried over into the programming languages of the day, and the concept is still widely in use within modern programming languages.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/data-segment] A computer program memory can be largely categorized into two sections: read-only and read/write.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/data-segment] This distinction grew from early systems holding their main program in read-only memory such as Mask ROM, EPROM, PROM or EEPROM.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/data-segment] As systems became more complex and programs were loaded from other media into RAM instead of executing from ROM, the idea that some portions of the program's memory should not be modified was retained.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/data-segment] These became the *.text* and *.rodata* segments of the program, and the remainder which could be written to divided into a number of other segments for specific tasks.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/data-segment] The **code segment**, also known as **text segment**, contains executable code and is generally read-only and fixed size.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/data-segment] The **data segment** contains initialized static variables, i.e. global variables and local static variables which have a defined value and can be modified.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/data-segment] The **BSS segment** contains uninitialized static data, both variables and constants, i.e. global variables and local static variables that are initialized to zero or do not have explicit initialization in source code.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/data-segment] The **heap segment** contains dynamically allocated memory, commonly begins at the end of the BSS segment and grows to larger addresses from there.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/data-segment] The heap segment is shared by all threads, shared libraries, and dynamically loaded modules in a process.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/data-segment] The **stack segment** contains the call stack, a LIFO structure, typically located in the higher parts of memory.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/data-segment] A "stack pointer" register tracks the top of the stack; it is adjusted each time a value is "pushed" onto the stack.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/data-segment] The set of values pushed for one function call is termed a "stack frame".
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/data-segment] A stack frame consists at minimum of a return address.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/data-segment] Automatic variables are also allocated on the stack.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/data-segment] The stack segment traditionally adjoined the heap segment and they grew towards each other; when the stack pointer met the heap pointer, free memory was exhausted.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/data-segment] With large address spaces and virtual memory techniques they tend to be placed more freely, but they still typically grow in a converging direction.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/data-segment] On the standard PC x86 architecture the stack grows toward address zero, meaning that more recent items, deeper in the call chain, are at numerically lower addresses and closer to the heap.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/data-segment] On some other architectures it grows the opposite direction.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/data-segment] Some interpreted languages offer a similar facility to the data segment, notably Perl and Ruby.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/data-segment] In these languages, including the line `__DATA__` (Perl) or `__END__` (Ruby, old Perl) marks the end of the code segment and the start of the data segment.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/data-segment] Only the contents prior to this line are executed, and the contents of the source file after this line are available as a file object: `PACKAGE::DATA` in Perl (e.g., `main::DATA`) and `DATA` in Ruby.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/data-segment] This can be considered a form of here document (a file literal).
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/memory-safety] Memory errors were first considered in the context of resource management (computing) and time-sharing systems, in an effort to avoid problems such as fork bombs.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/memory-safety] Developments were mostly theoretical until the Morris worm, which exploited a buffer overflow in fingerd.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/memory-safety] The field of computer security developed quickly thereafter, escalating with multitudes of new attacks such as the return-to-libc attack and defense techniques such as the non-executable stack and address space layout randomization.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/memory-safety] Randomization prevents most buffer overflow attacks and requires the attacker to use heap spraying or other application-dependent methods to obtain addresses, although its adoption has been slow.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/memory-safety] However, deployments of the technology are typically limited to randomizing libraries and the location of the stack.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/memory-safety] In 2019, a Microsoft security engineer reported that 70% of all security vulnerabilities were caused by memory safety issues.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/memory-safety] In 2020, a team at Google similarly reported that 70% of all "severe security bugs" in Chromium were caused by memory safety problems.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/memory-safety] Many other high-profile vulnerabilities and exploits in critical software have ultimately stemmed from a lack of memory safety, including Heartbleed and a long-standing privilege escalation bug in sudo.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/memory-safety] The pervasiveness and severity of vulnerabilities and exploits arising from memory safety issues have led several security researchers to describe identifying memory safety issues as "shooting fish in a barrel".
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/memory-safety] Some modern high-level programming languages are memory-safe by default, though not completely since they only check their own code and not the system they interact with.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/memory-safety] Automatic memory management in the form of garbage collection is the most common technique for preventing some of the memory safety problems, since it prevents common memory safety errors like use-after-free for all data allocated within the language runtime.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/memory-safety] However, the performance overhead of garbage collection makes these languages unsuitable for certain performance-critical applications.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/memory-safety] For languages that use manual memory management, memory safety is not usually guaranteed by the runtime.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/memory-safety] Instead, memory safety properties must either be guaranteed by the compiler via static program analysis and automated theorem proving or carefully managed by the programmer at runtime.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/memory-safety] For example, the Rust programming language implements a borrow checker to ensure memory safety, while C and C++ provide no memory safety guarantees.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/memory-safety] The substantial amount of software written in C and C++ has motivated the development of external static analysis tools like Coverity, which offers static memory analysis for C.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/memory-safety] DieHard, its redesign DieHarder, and the Allinea Distributed Debugging Tool are special heap allocators that allocate objects in their own random virtual memory page, allowing invalid reads and writes to be stopped and debugged at the exact instruction that causes them.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/memory-safety] Protection relies upon hardware memory protection and thus overhead is typically not substantial, although it can grow significantly if the program makes heavy use of allocation.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/memory-safety] Randomization provides only probabilistic protection against memory errors, but can often be easily implemented in existing software by relinking the binary.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/memory-safety] The memcheck tool of Valgrind uses an instruction set simulator and runs the compiled program in a memory-checking virtual machine, providing guaranteed detection of a subset of runtime memory errors.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/memory-safety] However, it typically slows the program down by a factor of 40, and furthermore must be explicitly informed of custom memory allocators.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/memory-safety] With access to the source code, libraries exist that collect and track legitimate values for pointers ("metadata") and check each pointer access against the metadata for validity, such as the Boehm garbage collector.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/memory-safety] In general, memory safety can be safely assured using tracing garbage collection and the insertion of runtime checks on every memory access; this approach has overhead, but less than that of Valgrind.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/memory-safety] All garbage-collected languages take this approach.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/memory-safety] For C and C++, many tools exist that perform a compile-time transformation of the code to do memory safety checks at runtime, such as CheckPointer and AddressSanitizer which imposes an average slowdown factor of 2.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/memory-safety] BoundWarden is a new spatial memory enforcement approach that utilizes a combination of compile-time transformation and runtime concurrent monitoring techniques.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/memory-safety] Fuzz testing is well-suited for finding memory safety bugs and is often used in combination with dynamic checkers such as AddressSanitizer.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/memory-safety] Some lists may also include **race conditions** (concurrent reads/writes to shared memory) as being part of memory safety (e.g., for access control).
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/memory-safety] The Rust programming language prevents many kinds of memory-based race conditions by default, because it ensures there is at most one writer *or* one or more readers.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/memory-safety] Many other programming languages, such as Java, do *not* automatically prevent memory-based race conditions, yet are still generally considered "memory safe" languages.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/memory-safety] Therefore, countering race conditions is generally *not* considered necessary for a language to be considered memory safe.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/pointer-computer-programming-p01] In computer science, a **pointer** is an object in many programming languages that stores a memory address.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/pointer-computer-programming-p01] This can be that of another value located in computer memory, or in some cases, that of memory-mapped computer hardware.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/pointer-computer-programming-p01] A pointer *references* a location in memory, and obtaining the value stored at that location is known as *dereferencing* the pointer.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/pointer-computer-programming-p01] As an analogy, a page number in a book's index could be considered a pointer to the corresponding page; dereferencing such a pointer would be done by flipping to the page with the given page number and reading the text found on that page.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/pointer-computer-programming-p01] The actual format and content of a pointer variable is dependent on the underlying computer architecture.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/pointer-computer-programming-p01] Using pointers significantly improves performance for repetitive operations, like traversing iterable data structures (e.g. strings, lookup tables, control tables, linked lists, and tree structures).
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/pointer-computer-programming-p01] In particular, it is often much cheaper in time and space to copy and dereference pointers than it is to copy and access the data to which the pointers point.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/pointer-computer-programming-p01] Pointers are also used to hold the addresses of entry points for called subroutines in procedural programming and for run-time linking to dynamic link libraries (DLLs).
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/pointer-computer-programming-p01] In object-oriented programming, pointers to functions are used for binding methods, often using virtual method tables.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/pointer-computer-programming-p01] A pointer is a simple, more concrete implementation of the more abstract *reference* data type.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/pointer-computer-programming-p01] Several languages, especially low-level languages, support some type of pointer, although some have more restrictions on their use than others.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/pointer-computer-programming-p01] Because pointers allow both protected and unprotected access to memory addresses, there are risks associated with using them, particularly in the latter case.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/pointer-computer-programming-p01] Primitive pointers are often stored in a format similar to an integer; however, attempting to dereference or "look up" such a pointer whose value is not a valid memory address could cause a program to crash (or contain invalid data).
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/pointer-computer-programming-p01] To alleviate this potential problem, as a matter of type safety, pointers are considered a separate type parameterized by the type of data they point to, even if the underlying representation is an integer.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/pointer-computer-programming-p01] Other measures may also be taken (such as validation and bounds checking), to verify that the pointer variable contains a value that is both a valid memory address and within the numerical range that the processor is capable of addressing.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/pointer-computer-programming-p01] In 1955, Soviet Ukrainian computer scientist Kateryna Yushchenko created the Address programming language that made possible indirect addressing and addresses of the highest rank – analogous to pointers.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/pointer-computer-programming-p01] This language was widely used on the Soviet computers.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/pointer-computer-programming-p01] However, it was unknown outside the Soviet Union and usually Harold Lawson is credited with the invention, in 1964, of the pointer.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/pointer-computer-programming-p01] In 2000, Lawson was presented the Computer Pioneer Award by the IEEE "[f]or inventing the pointer variable and introducing this concept into PL/I, thus providing for the first time, the capability to flexibly treat linked lists in a general-purpose high-level language".
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/pointer-computer-programming-p01] His seminal paper on the concepts appeared in the June 1967 issue of CACM entitled: PL/I List Processing.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/pointer-computer-programming-p01] According to the Oxford English Dictionary, the **word** *pointer* first appeared in print as a *stack pointer* in a technical memorandum by the System Development Corporation.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/pointer-computer-programming-p01] In computer science, a pointer is a kind of reference.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/pointer-computer-programming-p01] A *data primitive* (or just *primitive*) is any datum that can be read from or written to computer memory using one memory access (for instance, both a *byte* and a *word* are primitives).
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/pointer-computer-programming-p01] A *data aggregate* (or just *aggregate*) is a group of primitives that are logically contiguous in memory and that are viewed collectively as one datum (for instance, an aggregate could be 3 logically contiguous bytes, the values of which represent the 3 coordinates of a point in space).
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/pointer-computer-programming-p01] When an aggregate is entirely composed of the same type of primitive, the aggregate may be called an *array*; in a sense, a multi-byte *word* primitive is an array of bytes, and some programs use words in this way.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/pointer-computer-programming-p01] In the context of these definitions, a *byte* is the smallest primitive; each memory address specifies a different byte.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/pointer-computer-programming-p01] The memory address of the initial byte of a datum is considered the memory address (or *base memory address*) of the entire datum.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/pointer-computer-programming-p01] A *memory pointer* (or just *pointer*) is a primitive, the value of which is intended to be used as a memory address; it is said that *a pointer points to a memory address*.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/pointer-computer-programming-p01] It is also said that *a pointer points to a datum [in memory]* when the pointer's value is the datum's memory address.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/pointer-computer-programming-p01] More generally, a pointer is a kind of reference, and it is said that *a pointer references a datum stored somewhere in memory*; to obtain that datum is *to dereference the pointer*.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/pointer-computer-programming-p01] The feature that separates pointers from other kinds of reference is that a pointer's value is meant to be interpreted as a memory address, which is a rather low-level concept.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/pointer-computer-programming-p01] References serve as a level of indirection: A pointer's value determines which memory address (that is, which datum) is to be used in a calculation.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/pointer-computer-programming-p01] Because indirection is a fundamental aspect of algorithms, pointers are often expressed as a fundamental data type in programming languages; in statically (or strongly) typed programming languages, the type of a pointer determines the type of the datum to which the pointer points.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/pointer-computer-programming-p01] Pointers are a very thin abstraction on top of the addressing capabilities provided by most modern architectures.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/pointer-computer-programming-p01] The system would then also provide an operation to retrieve the value stored in the memory unit at a given address (usually utilizing the machine's general-purpose registers).
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/pointer-computer-programming-p01] In the usual case, a pointer is large enough to hold more addresses than there are units of memory in the system.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/pointer-computer-programming-p01] This introduces the possibility that a program may attempt to access an address which corresponds to no unit of memory, either because not enough memory is installed (i.e. beyond the range of available memory) or the architecture does not support such addresses.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/pointer-computer-programming-p01] The first case may, in certain platforms such as the Intel x86 architecture, be called a segmentation fault (segfault).
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/pointer-computer-programming-p01] The second case is possible in the current implementation of AMD64, where pointers are 64 bit long and addresses only extend to 48 bits.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/pointer-computer-programming-p01] Pointers must conform to certain rules (canonical addresses), so if a non-canonical pointer is dereferenced, the processor raises a general protection fault.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/pointer-computer-programming-p01] On the other hand, some systems have more units of memory than there are addresses.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/pointer-computer-programming-p01] In this case, a more complex scheme such as memory segmentation or paging is employed to use different parts of the memory at different times.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/pointer-computer-programming-p01] The last incarnations of the x86 architecture support up to 36 bits of physical memory addresses, which were mapped to the 32-bit linear address space through the PAE paging mechanism.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/pointer-computer-programming-p01] Thus, only 1/16 of the possible total memory may be accessed at a time.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/pointer-computer-programming-p01] In order to provide a consistent interface, some architectures provide memory-mapped I/O, which allows some addresses to refer to units of memory while others refer to device registers of other devices in the computer.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/pointer-computer-programming-p01] There are analogous concepts such as file offsets, array indices, and remote object references that serve some of the same purposes as addresses for other types of objects.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/pointer-computer-programming-p01] Pointers are directly supported without restrictions in languages such as PL/I, C, C++, Pascal, FreeBASIC, and implicitly in most assembly languages.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/pointer-computer-programming-p01] They are used mainly to construct references, which in turn are fundamental to construct nearly all data structures, and to pass data between different parts of a program.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/pointer-computer-programming-p01] In functional programming languages that rely heavily on lists, data references are managed abstractly by using primitive constructs like cons and the corresponding elements car and cdr, which can be thought of as specialised pointers to the first and second components of a cons-cell.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/pointer-computer-programming-p01] This gives rise to some of the idiomatic "flavour" of functional programming.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/pointer-computer-programming-p01] By structuring data in such cons-lists, these languages facilitate recursive means for building and processing data—for example, by recursively accessing the head and tail elements of lists of lists; e.g.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/pointer-computer-programming-p01] By contrast, memory management based on pointer dereferencing in some approximation of an array of memory addresses facilitates treating variables as slots into which data can be assigned imperatively.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/pointer-computer-programming-p01] When dealing with arrays, the critical lookup operation typically involves a stage called *address calculation* which involves constructing a pointer to the desired data element in the array.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/pointer-computer-programming-p01] In other data structures, such as linked lists, pointers are used as references to explicitly tie one piece of the structure to another.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/pointer-computer-programming-p01] Pointers are used to pass parameters by reference.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/pointer-computer-programming-p01] This is useful if the programmer wants a function's modifications to a parameter to be visible to the function's caller.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/pointer-computer-programming-p01] This is also useful for returning multiple values from a function.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/pointer-computer-programming-p01] Pointers can also be used to allocate and deallocate dynamic variables and arrays in memory.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/pointer-computer-programming-p01] Since a variable will often become redundant after it has served its purpose, it is a waste of memory to keep it, and therefore it is good practice to deallocate it (using the original pointer reference) when it is no longer needed.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/pointer-computer-programming-p01] Failure to do so may result in a *memory leak* (where available free memory gradually, or in severe cases rapidly, diminishes because of an accumulation of numerous redundant memory blocks).
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/pointer-computer-programming-p01] This declares a variable `ptr` that stores a pointer to an object of type `int`.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/pointer-computer-programming-p01] Other types can be used in place of `int`; for example, `bool *ptr` would declare a pointer to an object of type `bool`.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/pointer-computer-programming-p01] After a pointer has been declared, it can be assigned an address.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/pointer-computer-programming-p01] Both `int *x, y;` and `int* x, y;` declare `x` to be a pointer to `int`, but declare `y` to be an `int`.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/pointer-computer-programming-p01] This is because the `*` applies only to the variable immediately following it.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/pointer-computer-programming-p01] The asterisk can also be used on the left-hand side of an assignment to change the object `a` without having to be in the same scope.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/pointer-computer-programming-p01] If `a` is accessed later, its new value will be 8.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/pointer-computer-programming-p01] Because the C language does not specify an implicit initialization for objects of automatic storage duration, pointer variables can sometimes point to unexpected locations, causing undefined behavior.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/pointer-computer-programming-p01] To combat this, pointers are sometimes initialized with a null pointer value, represented in C by the `NULL` macro; in C23 and later, `nullptr` is also available as an alternative, which is of type `nullptr_t`.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/pointer-computer-programming-p01] Dereferencing a null pointer produces undefined behavior, which can result in unpredictable bugs and results.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/pointer-computer-programming-p01] This example may be clearer if memory is examined directly.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/pointer-computer-programming-p01] Assume that `a` is located at address 0x8130 in memory and `ptr` at 0x8134; also assume this is a 32-bit machine such that an int is 32-bits wide.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/pointer-computer-programming-p01] Clearly, accessing `a` will yield the value of 8 because the previous instruction modified the contents of `a` by way of the pointer `ptr`.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/pointer-computer-programming-p01] When setting up data structures like lists, queues and trees, it is necessary to have pointers to help manage how the structure is implemented and controlled.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/pointer-computer-programming-p01] Typical examples of pointers are start pointers, end pointers, and stack pointers.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/pointer-computer-programming-p01] Relative addresses are a form of manual memory segmentation, and share many of its advantages and disadvantages.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/pointer-computer-programming-p01] A two-byte offset, containing a 16-bit, unsigned integer, can be used to provide relative addressing for up to 64 KiB (216 bytes) of a data structure.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/pointer-computer-programming-p01] Generally, though, such schemes are a lot of trouble, and for convenience to the programmer absolute addresses (and underlying that, a *flat address space*) is preferred.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/pointer-computer-programming-p01] A one byte offset, such as the hexadecimal ASCII value of a character (e.g.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/pointer-computer-programming-p01] X'29') can be used to point to an alternative integer value (or index) in an array (e.g., X'01').
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/pointer-computer-programming-p01] In this way, characters can be very efficiently translated from 'raw data' to a usable sequential index and then to an absolute address without a lookup table.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/pointer-computer-programming-p01] This allocates a block of five integers and names the block `a`; the expression `a` evaluates, in most contexts, as a pointer to the first element of the block.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/pointer-computer-programming-p01] Another common use of pointers is to point to dynamically allocated memory from malloc which returns a consecutive block of memory of no less than the requested size that can be used as an array.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/pointer-computer-programming-p01] While, when used as an operand for most operators, an array evaluates as a pointer to the first element of the array, this is not the case for the `sizeof` operator.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/pointer-computer-programming-p01] In this example, `sizeof(a)` will evaluate to `5 * sizeof(int)` (the size of the array), while `sizeof(ptr)` will evaluate to `sizeof(int *)`, the size of the pointer itself.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/pointer-computer-programming-p01] Represented here are five integers: 2, 4, 3, 1, and 5.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/pointer-computer-programming-p01] These five integers occupy 32 bits (4 bytes) each with the least-significant byte stored first (this is a little-endian CPU architecture) and are stored consecutively starting at address 0x1000.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/pointer-computer-programming-p01] The last example is how to access the contents of `a`.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/pointer-computer-programming-p01] Below is an example definition of a linked list in C.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/pointer-computer-programming-p01] where `Nil` is the empty list, and `Cons a (LinkedList a)` is a cons cell of type `a` with another link also of type `a`.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/pointer-computer-programming-p01] The definition with references, however, is type-checked and does not use potentially confusing signal values.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/pointer-computer-programming-p01] For this reason, data structures in C are usually dealt with via wrapper functions, which are carefully checked for correctness.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/pointer-computer-programming-p01] Pointers can be used to pass variables by their address, allowing their value to be changed.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/pointer-computer-programming-p01] In some programs, the required amount of memory depends on what *the user* may enter.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/pointer-computer-programming-p01] In such cases the programmer needs to allocate memory dynamically.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/pointer-computer-programming-p01] This is done by allocating memory at the *heap* rather than on the *stack*, where variables usually are stored (although variables can also be stored in the CPU registers).
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/pointer-computer-programming-p01] Dynamic memory allocation can only be made through pointers, and names – like with common variables – cannot be given.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/pointer-computer-programming-p01] Pointers are used to store and manage the addresses of dynamically allocated blocks of memory.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/pointer-computer-programming-p01] Such blocks are used to store data objects or arrays of objects.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/pointer-computer-programming-p01] Most structured and object-oriented languages provide an area of memory, called the *heap* or *free store*, from which objects are dynamically allocated.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/pointer-computer-programming-p01] The example C code below illustrates how structure objects are dynamically allocated and referenced.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/pointer-computer-programming-p01] The standard C library provides the function `malloc()` for allocating memory blocks from the heap.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/pointer-computer-programming-p01] It takes the size of an object to allocate as a parameter and returns a pointer to a newly allocated block of memory suitable for storing the object, or it returns a null pointer if the allocation failed.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/pointer-computer-programming-p01] The code below illustrates how memory objects are dynamically deallocated, i.e., returned to the heap or free store.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/pointer-computer-programming-p01] The standard C library provides the function `free()` for deallocating a previously allocated memory block and returning it back to the heap.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/pointer-computer-programming-p01] On some computing architectures, pointers can be used to directly manipulate memory or memory-mapped devices.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/pointer-computer-programming-p01] Assigning addresses to pointers is an invaluable tool when programming microcontrollers.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/pointer-computer-programming-p01] In the mid-1980s, using the BIOS to access the video capabilities of PCs was slow.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/pointer-computer-programming-p01] Applications that were display-intensive typically used to access CGA video memory directly by casting the hexadecimal constant 0xB8000 to a pointer to an array of 80 unsigned 16-bit int values.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/pointer-computer-programming-p01] Each value consisted of an ASCII code in the low byte, and a colour in the high byte.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/pointer-computer-programming-p01] Control tables that are used to control program flow usually make extensive use of pointers.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/pointer-computer-programming-p01] The pointers, usually embedded in a table entry, may, for instance, be used to hold the entry points to subroutines to be executed, based on certain conditions defined in the same table entry.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/pointer-computer-programming-p01] The pointers can however be simply indexes to other separate, but associated, tables comprising an array of the actual addresses or the addresses themselves (depending upon the programming language constructs available).
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/pointer-computer-programming-p01] They can also be used to point to earlier table entries (as in loop processing) or forward to skip some table entries (as in a switch or "early" exit from a loop).
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/pointer-computer-programming-p01] For this latter purpose, the "pointer" may simply be the table entry number itself and can be transformed into an actual address by simple arithmetic.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/pointer-computer-programming-p01] In many languages, pointers have the additional restriction that the object they point to has a specific type.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/pointer-computer-programming-p01] For example, a pointer may be declared to point to an integer; the language will then attempt to prevent the programmer from pointing it to objects which are not integers, such as floating-point numbers, eliminating some errors.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/pointer-computer-programming-p01] `money` would be an integer pointer and `bags` would be a char pointer.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/pointer-computer-programming-p01] because `money` and `bags` were declared with different types.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/pointer-computer-programming-p01] which says to cast the integer pointer of `money` to a char pointer and assign to `bags`.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/pointer-computer-programming-p01] A 2005 draft of the C standard requires that casting a pointer derived from one type to one of another type should maintain the alignment correctness for both types (6.3.2.3 Pointers, par.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/pointer-computer-programming-p01] In languages that allow pointer arithmetic, arithmetic on pointers takes into account the size of the type.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/pointer-computer-programming-p01] For example, adding an integer number to a pointer produces another pointer that points to an address that is higher by that number times the size of the type.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/pointer-computer-programming-p01] This allows us to easily compute the address of elements of an array of a given type, as was shown in the C arrays example above.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/pointer-computer-programming-p01] When a pointer of one type is cast to another type of a different size, the programmer should expect that pointer arithmetic will be calculated differently.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/pointer-computer-programming-p01] In C, for example, if the `money` array starts at 0x2000 and `sizeof(int)` is 4 bytes whereas `sizeof(char)` is 1 byte, then `money + 1` will point to 0x2004, but `bags + 1` would point to 0x2001.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/pointer-computer-programming-p01] Other risks of casting include loss of data when "wide" data is written to "narrow" locations (e.g.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/pointer-computer-programming-p01] `bags[0] = 65537;`), unexpected results when bit-shifting values, and comparison problems, especially with signed vs unsigned values.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/pointer-computer-programming-p01] Although it is impossible in general to determine at compile-time which casts are safe, some languages store run-time type information which can be used to confirm that these dangerous casts are valid at runtime.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/pointer-computer-programming-p01] Other languages merely accept a conservative approximation of safe casts, or none at all.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/pointer-computer-programming-p01] In C and C++, even if two pointers compare as equal that doesn't mean they are equivalent.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/pointer-computer-programming-p01] In these languages *and* LLVM, the rule is interpreted to mean that "just because two pointers point to the same address, does not mean they are equal in the sense that they can be used interchangeably", the difference between the pointers referred to as their *provenance*.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/pointer-computer-programming-p01] Casting to an integer type such as `uintptr_t` is implementation-defined and the comparison it provides does not provide any more insight as to whether the two pointers are interchangeable.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/pointer-computer-programming-p01] In addition, further conversion to bytes and arithmetic will throw off optimizers trying to keep track the use of pointers, a problem still being elucidated in academic research.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/pointer-computer-programming-p01] As a pointer allows a program to attempt to access an object that may not be defined, pointers can be the origin of a variety of programming errors.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/pointer-computer-programming-p01] However, the usefulness of pointers is so great that it can be difficult to perform programming tasks without them.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/pointer-computer-programming-p01] Consequently, many languages have created constructs designed to provide some of the useful features of pointers without some of their pitfalls, also sometimes referred to as *pointer hazards*.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/pointer-computer-programming-p01] In this context, pointers that directly address memory (as used in this article) are referred to as **raw pointers** or **naked pointer**, by contrast with smart pointers or other variants.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/pointer-computer-programming-p01] One major problem with pointers is that as long as they can be directly manipulated as a number, they can be made to point to unused addresses or to data which is being used for other purposes.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/pointer-computer-programming-p01] Array indexing is handled as a special case.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/pointer-computer-programming-p01] A pointer which does not have any address assigned to it is called a wild pointer.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/pointer-computer-programming-p01] Any attempt to use such uninitialized pointers can cause unexpected behavior, either because the initial value is not a valid address, or because using it may damage other parts of the program.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/pointer-computer-programming-p01] The result is often a segmentation fault, storage violation or wild branch (if used as a function pointer or branch address).
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/pointer-computer-programming-p01] In systems with explicit memory allocation, it is possible to create a dangling pointer by deallocating the memory region it points into.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/pointer-computer-programming-p01] This type of pointer is dangerous and subtle because a deallocated memory region may contain the same data as it did before it was deallocated but may be then reallocated and overwritten by unrelated code, unknown to the earlier code.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/pointer-computer-programming-p01] Languages with garbage collection prevent this type of error because deallocation is performed automatically when there are no more references in scope.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/pointer-computer-programming-p01] In languages that abstract away pointers and pointer arithmetic, such as Java, one can use iterators, which can be seen as a safer means of iterating over a segment of memory or a collection without using direct pointer access.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/pointer-computer-programming-p01] Many languages, even those with pointers, such as C++, C# and Rust, have iterators for collections.
[src:address-space-layout-randomization/pointer-computer-programming-p01] In C++ the iterator can overload `operator++`, similar to the traditional syntax of incrementing a pointer in C.
